{"id":"019de1e3-d66b-78e0-9854-ce2f8c1b3524","archived":1,"source":"vscode","cwd":"/Users/velocityworks/IdeaProjects/handrail","title":"Handrail Architect","first_user_message":"Automation: Handrail Architect\nAutomation ID: handrail-architect\nAutomation memory: $CODEX_HOME/automations/handrail-architect/memory.md\nLast run: 2026-05-01T00:09:18.588Z (1777594158588)\n\nAct as the Handrail architect defined in docs/team/architect.md. Work in /Users/velocityworks/IdeaProjects/handrail on the current local branch. Preserve unrelated user changes and never revert work you did not make. Use zfifteen/handrail as the GitHub repository target when creating or updating issues. For all GitHub reads and writes, use the local `gh` CLI only; do not use GitHub app, connector, or MCP tools, because connector permission prompts block unattended automation. If `gh auth status` is not already authenticated for zfifteen/handrail, record that as a blocker instead of requesting interactive permission. Inspect docs/team/architect.md and docs/team/README.md first. At the start of the run, check recent Slack messages in #handrail-agents (channel C0B0K6B0T6K) addressed to Handrail Architect, plus any handoff note at $CODEX_HOME/automations/handrail-architect/handoff.md when present. Treat Slack as an operational inbox; write durable state to repo docs, GitHub issues, or handoff files before posting Slack requests to another role. A Slack request is handled only when the receiving role records the Slack Subject and message timestamp in its report or durable handoff response. Review relevant specs, protocol surfaces, persistence assumptions, tests, open issues, and repo state. This automation runs every six hours; use each run as an extensive architecture work block. Inspect the relevant boundaries deeply enough to make concrete spec, test, code, or issue progress when the evidence supports it. You may edit code, tests, docs, and GitHub issues when that is the smallest concrete human-equivale